1. Introduction¶

Bike-sharing businesses have been blooming across North America in recent years. The usage of Bike Sharing can help reduce the consumption of natural sources and air pollution in sustainable cities. With the known benefits of introducing bike-sharing to urban cities, it is crucial to improve policies that will make bike-sharing more effective and accessible to its users.

Using the Seoul Bike Sharing Demand Data Set from UCI Machine Learning Repository, we want to study the factors that affect bike-sharing behavior in order to keep a stable supply of rental bikes. The dataset contains information on the number of bikes rented each hour of the day, with various weather condition factors (i.e. Temperature, Humidity, Windspeed, Visibility, Dewpoint, Solar radiation, Snowfall, and Rainfall) during the hour recorded.

In order to make our results comparable to similar studies conducted on bike sharing demand, we inspect various research articles which focused on the main environmental factors affecting this demand. One existing research from a university student group explored “the impact of economic, environmental and social factors for students cycling” to drive a well-thought design for the bike-sharing service [2]. Another research which we thoroughly scanned was focused more on predicting bike sharing demand using neural networks. Upon gaining more insight from both the studies, we formulated the following research questions:

1) Are temperature, wind speed and precipitation the only weather conditions that significantly affect Bike Sharing Demand?
¶

2) Which weather condition factors, when used as explanatory variables, create the model that yields the most accurate real-time predictions of bike sharing demand?
¶

The data set which will be using is the Seoul Bike Sharing Demand Data from UCI machine learning repository. After cleaning and wrangling the data set, it has the following variables of interest:

  • date: dd/mm/yyyy
  • bike_count: Count of bikes rented at each hour
  • hour: Hour of the day
  • temperature: Temperature in Celsius
  • humidity: Humidity percentage
  • wind_speed: Wind speed in $\text{m/s}$
  • visibility: 10 mile visibility
  • dew_point_temp - The temperature to which air must be cooled to become saturated with water vapor, assuming constant air pressure and water content.
  • radiation - Electromagnetic radiation emitted by the sun. Measured in $\text{MJ}/\text{m}^2$
  • rain - Precipitation in $\text{mm}$
  • snow - Snowfall in $\text{cm}$
  • season - Winter, Spring, Summer, Autumn
  • holiday - Holiday/No holiday

options(repr.plot.width = 14, repr.plot.height = 7)

count_by_hour_plot <- 
    bike_data |>
    group_by(hour) |>
    summarise(mean_bike_count = mean(bike_count)) |>
    ggplot(aes(x = hour, y = mean_bike_count)) +
    geom_bar(aes(fill = hour), color = "black", stat = "identity") +
    scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("#42518C", "#FF7040", "#FFE3A7", "#FFF3D0", "#54498B", "#332665")) +
    labs(x = "\nHour",
         y = "Mean Bike Count",
         title = "Average Demand for Bikes During the Day") +
    geom_text(aes(label = round(mean_bike_count, 1)), vjust = -0.5, size = 4) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-0.5, 23.5),
                       breaks = seq(0, 23),
                       minor_breaks = seq(1, 23, 1)) +
    scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0, .1))) +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(legend.position = "none",
          plot.title = element_text(size = 22),
          axis.text = element_text(size = 15),
          axis.title = element_text(size = 15))

count_by_hour_plot

From the above graph, we can easily conclude that the number of bike uses varies greatly throughout the day, especially between the morning and evening rush hours and other times of the day, thus confirming the strong relationship between bike use and time of day.

count_x_temp_plot

`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

From the scatter plot we can conclude the following that there is a roughly positive linear relationship between the number of bike uses and the temperature. As the temperature rises, the demand for bike use increases. We can easily distinguish their seasonal differences by the seasonal colors in the graph above, with less bike use in winter and, conversely, the greatest bike use in summer. There is no big difference in temperature between autumn and spring, and their data are distributed overlapping between winter and summer, so the number of bicycle use is almost the same in spring and autumn.

Methods: Plan¶

For our report, we are planning to build a generative model for inferential analysis after which we will perform model selection to build the most optimal predictive model.

Since we intend to use Linear Regression for both the analyses, we will first check whether our data fulfills all the necessary assumptions of Linear Regression. After performing diagnostics to detect any potential problems such as confounding factors or heteroscedasticity, we will continue with our inferential analysis where we split the data into a training set and a selection set. Using the selection set, we create different nested LR models and compare them via F-tests. After obtaining the most optimal model, we will check its goodness of fit using the training set.

Next, we will build the most optimal predictive model given the weather condition factors available in our data set. The prediction analysis will involve the forward selection method to generate a predictive model using the training set. Here, we will check for the model with the lowest mean squared error yielding the most accurate predictions. After obtaining the most optimal predictive model, we will evaluate its ability to predict by making predictions on the response of the selection set (which will be used as the test set).

We expect to discover two different models: 1) The most optimal generative model for inference 2) The most optimal predictive model for prediction

The first model will help us decide whether temperature, precipitation and wind speed are the only significant factors affecting bike sharing demand while the second model will allow us to make real-time predictions on any new data received.

Our report will be trustworthy as we will check for all assumptions of Linear Regression in order to produce a reliable generative/predictive model. Using stratification strategies, correlation plots and residual vs fitted values plots, we will tackle and diagnose problems such as confounding factors, multi-collinearity and heteroscedasticity well before going into our analyses.
